<TEXT>
the cochairman of the troubled joffrey ballet 
has resigned the new york times reported in fridays editions 
anthony a bliss announced his resignation thursday and told the 
times that david h murdock the other cochairman had also 
resigned and that frank w lynch vice chairman of the board had 
either resigned or was about to 
the three executives are said to be among those opposed to the 
continuing directorship of gerald arpino who founded the company 
with the late robert joffrey 
arpino earlier this month resigned as artistic director of the 
ballet and withdrew his works and joffreys from the ballets 
repertory he quit after the joffrey board of directors voted to 
set up an operating committee that would run the company in place 
of both arpino and the 55member board 
but arpino remains artistic director of the companys ballet 
school and negotiations are continuing on his future role in the 
joffrey 
arpino has been a dancer and choreographer with the modern 
ballet company since its early days in the mid1950s however 
critics and dance buffs alike have often called his works 
pedestrian instead of inspired and without structure purpose or 
artistry 
the joffrey like many dance companies has financial problems 
based in new york and los angeles it faces a deficit of about 2 
million 
murdock had agreed to close the deficit with gifts loans and 
fundraising over three years the new york times previously 
reported 
