<TEXT>
thomas jefferson once ran a lottery to pay off 
his personal debts calling it a wonderful concept because it 
lays taxation only on the willing 
now some members of congress are talking about a national 
lottery as a possible way to raise money without raising taxes 
especially after george bushs campaign pledge read my lips no 
new taxes 
but visions of megajackpots aside the very idea of a national 
game seems like a bad gamble for states already in the lottery 
business and for religious and social groups 
we oppose the idea said michael carr director of the 
michigan lottery and head of the north american association of 
state and provincial lotteries we would prefer the money stay in 
the states clearly it would be competition 
lotto america a 10state group that pools its resources to 
offer bigger jackpots also views a national game as a bad bet 
i dont think theres enough room in the marketplace said 
jim davey director of the oregon lottery and vice president of 
lotto america a national lottery would significantly cut into 
lotto america sales theres probably a limit on the disposable 
income people have for gambling 
lotteries are now a billiondollar industry thirtyone states 
and the district of columbia offer games and sales this year are 
expected to top 20 billion four times what they were in 1982 
lottery officials say 
most states make a profit of 30 percent to 40 percent that is 
earmarked for such things as education and aid to the elderly and 
some congressmen are itching to get in on the action 
sen alan simpson of wyoming the senates no 2 republican 
said tuesday a a national lottery was a possible revenue source to 
plug into the federal budget 
rep austin murphy dpa plans to try again with a national 
lottery bill he first suggested in 1985 
attempts at starting a national lottery have failed in the past 
in large part because rep dan rostenkowski dill chairman of 
the house ways and means committee is adamantly opposed to them 
and his panel has jurisdiction in the house 
murphys bill would return a share of the take to states selling 
tickets the congressman recognizes that any measure that lacks 
such a provision doesnt have a chance according to mike 
johns a staff member of the house labor standards subcomittee 
but there are many opponents who see lotteries as a shell game 
that tax the poor 
a lottery is the sale of an illusion to poor people who view 
it as the only possibility of breaking out of the cycle of poverty 
they live in said weston ware of the baptist christian life 
commission in texas its bad public policy bad social policy 
and bad moral policy 
valerie lorenz executive director of the national center for 
pathological gambling in baltimore also thinks the idea is a bad 
one 
it is absolutely foolhardy to legalize any type of gambling 
without studying the social and economic costs of promoting an 
addictive process she said the government would be promoting 
an addiction 
still the chance to win instant riches by buying a ticket has 
giltedged appeal and taxpayers are weary of shelling out more and 
more to the government 
the resistance to gambling in increasingly counterbalanced by 
the desire not to pay more taxes said emory university history 
professor dan carter 
a 1984 gallup poll commissioned by the trade magazine gaming and 
wagering business found that 62 percent of americans supported an 
annual national game and 26 percent opposed it 
but paul dworin the magazines publisher said such sentiments 
would not be enough to offset political realities 
i dont think it has a chance dworin said will utah 
allow a national lottery to operate will some of the southern 
states in the bible belt 
this wouldnt be the first congress to try to hit the jackpot 
with a quick fix 
in 1776 the continental congress approved a lottery to raise 
10 million for george washingtons army it was abandoned because 
most colonists couldnt afford the 10 ticket and the wealthier 
ones who were tories had no desire to aid the rebellion said 
john scarne in his complete guide to gambling 
lotteries also helped finance ivy league schools such as 
harvard dartmouth and princeton but games were outlawed in the 
19th century because many of them were fixed 
new hampshire reintroduced gambling in modern times with a 
statewide sweepstakes in 1964 for public schools 
but a lottery would have to rake in a lot of money to put a dent 
in the 301 trillion national debt a congressional research 
service study in 1985 said every american over age 16 would have to 
spend 2041 on the game to eliminate a deficit of 185 billion 
and h roy kaplan an associate professor at the florida 
institute of technology said the most optimistic estimates from a 
lottery game would not be enough to cover the interest on the 
national debt 
in realistic terms the national debt is unapproachable in 
terms of a lotterys ability to diminish it kaplan said 
</TEXT>
