<TEXT>
who steals william wardhams work steals 
art who steals his raw materials steals trash indeed 
wardham is the first artistinresidence at san franciscos huge 
trash transfer station near candlestick park hes happily been 
welding metal scraps into more than half a dozen works already on 
display near his work area 
there is so much activity so much history in this the 
48yearold sculptor said holding crumpled chrome that once was a 
grocery cart you immediately ask yourself how it got that way 
was it crushed by a hydraulic press here in the yard or did 
something happen to the grocery cart 
jacqueline tripp head of the program for norcal solid waste 
systems inc said the goal is to get people to start thinking 
about recycling to reduce the amount of garbage they generate 
its important to be aware of all the waste out there and that 
some of it can be reclaimed tripp said we have to find a 
means to extend the life of our landfills 
wardham says the smell bothers him occasionally although the 
2000 tons of trash received every day is deodorized somewhat by a 
bubblegum smelling aerator that also controls dust with moisture 
tripp said norcal plans to pay artistsinresidence an average 
of 2000 a month for a one to sixmonth stint at the site where 
trash is dumped and then shipped to landfills at other sites 
completed works will remain at the solidwaste transfer station 
as part of a growing exhibit open to visitors including school 
children and civic leaders according to tripp 
we renovated a building for an artists studio right on site 
here she said i think well see some interesting pieces of 
art created 
jo hanson a longtime conceptual artist who helps select 
artists for the dump project proposed it out of her love of 
creating art from trash she found on the streets in front of her 
san francisco house 
by bringing together the environment and art were carrying a 
message that will make people more thoughtful about materials 
she said there is an infinite supply of material here both in 
quantity and variety 
in 1970 hanson said she was sweeping the sidewalk in front of 
her home when she began to see art in what was there blowing 
past me every day 
ive studied garbage in the streets of other big cities and 
san francisco has unique trash she said people dont hide 
their private lives here 
just from the stuff on the sidewalks you can follow the 
progress of some peoples affairs including their drug dealings 
and sex lives 
hanson and wardham say working with used materials is more 
challenging because the items have a history that can influence the 
artist 
you can do conceptual things that relate to where the trash 
comes from and where it goes hanson said recently ive begun 
working with metal that has been run over in the streets enough to 
make it into interesting shapes theres an urban energy to the 
pieces 
so far hanson has received 30 applicants from artists 
interesting in working at the dump i think weve always had a 
more progressive outlook here she said this is just another 
innovative art program 
