censorship ended with the fall of 
nicolae ceausescu in december but the opposition says state 
control of television and major newspapers and of newspaper 
distribution is just as effective 
spokesmen for independent news outlets and parties say telling 
the opposition story is extremely difficult as romania approaches 
its first free elections in 44 years scheduled for may 20 
the chief target of criticism is the national salvation front 
which dominates the interim government and is suspected by many of 
seeking to bring back a milder form of communism 
many ranking members of the front including interim president 
ion iliescu are former communists who had been critical of 
ceausescu front leaders profess democratic ideals including a 
commitment to freedom of the press 
the human rights law group based in washington dc said 
after a factfinding tour in late april that many romanians 
believed the front controlled the government 
it said the fronts advantages are amplified by the 
governments control of television printing presses and newsprint 
distribution of national and opposition print media international 
communications networks and air and ground transport 
there are widespread complaints that the newspapers 
distributed by the government especially those of opposition 
parties and certain independent papers often fail to reach their 
destination are not delivered promptly or are returned when they 
could have been sold the monitoring group said 
several journalists working for independent dailies or 
opposition party papers echoed those concerns in recent interviews 
on television representatives of opposing political parties 
have three minutes to tell their story from scripts held in 
their hand said petre mihai bacanu president of the 
4000member independent journalists union 
mr iliescu could grin on the screen all day and nobody at the 
television would mind he said 
supporters of the front say iliescu and other senior officials 
get more coverage because national leaders make more news than 
obscure candidates for parliament 
several journalists said even coverage of news events was biased 
in the fronts favor 
one example cited was a demonstration organized by the liberal 
party at which the camera dwelt at length on barefooted gypsies in 
the crowd most romanians think of gypsies as idlers and thieves 
images of roses flattering graphics and stirring music were 
added to taped coverage of a front rally the journalists said 
distribution of independent or opposition daily newspapers was 
one of the problems mentioned most often 
bacanu is a member of the group that publishes romania libera 
which has a circulation of 850000 and is the largest paper 
regularly critical of the government 
he snorted when asked whether copies were reaching readers in 
the provinces people on the train simply throw them off 
becanu said 
gelu netea manager of the liberal party paper vitorul said 
state trucking companies were run by neocommunists meaning 
supporters of the front who did not honor contracts to deliver the 
newspaper nationwide 
in bucharest the press distributor regularly either doesnt 
take our copies or only a small amount netea said during an 
interview in his office he gestured at stacks of newspapers 
several days old 
other government companies with agreements to distribute 80000 
copies nationally will take only 40000 on a given day and then 
will wait up to five days to take them to newsstands he said 
officials and supporters of the government denied the charges 
both sides agree the staterun presses which turned out only a 
halfdozen dailies in ceausescus day are woefully inadequate for 
printing the more than 700 newspapers now being published 
some typesetting machines at the central printing plant date 
from the 1940s and much of the lead is melted in an antiquated 
gasfired furnace 
welcome to gutenbergs era a foreman on the printing floor 
told a western reporter who was touring the plant 
