<TEXT>
months of complex financial negotiations 
between the united states and iran produced a tentative 105 
million settlement of more than 2000 us small claims pending 
since the 1979 islamic revolution the state department says 
the package deal also includes a tentative agreement to pay 
400000 to settle 108 iranian claims against the united states 
deputy spokesman richard boucher said wednesday 
the bush administration repeatedly has declared it will make no 
deals to secure the release of the us hostages in lebanon 
believed held by proiranian militants and that the claims 
negotiations are not related to the hostage situation in any way 
nonetheless the tentative accord on the small claims is a step 
toward settling about 16 billion in larger claims that have been a 
major irritant between iran and the united states for a decade 
officials of both countries said in the hague netherlands site of 
the iranunited states claims tribunal 
in washington a department official who commented on condition 
of anonymity said he could not predict whether resolving the claims 
issue will result in the release of hostages or was in any way 
connected with the recent release of two captives 
i have no way to speculate the official said 
the agreement covers 2370 us claims government and private 
the department said with 50 million going to private claims and 
55 million to us government claims 
us officials in the hague said an additional 400 or so claims 
not before the tribunal also are covered 
the actual text of the agreement on claims of up to 250000 
must still be written signed and then ratified by the tribunal 
the panel was established under the 1981 algiers accord that won 
the release of 52 americans held captive at the us embassy in 
tehran for 444 days 
the proposed settlement is the result of many months of 
effort boucher said noting that negotiators discussed the issue 
at meetings held almost every month since last april 
he said it is not clear how long it will take to wrap up final 
details of the tentative agreement 
state department officials have said repeatedly that there is no 
link between the negotiations to settle the claims and the hostage 
situation they maintain that the talks at the hague are not a 
forum in which hostages are discussed 
boucher said that among the us government claims now near 
settlement are loans made to iran by the agency for international 
development the private claims included those for private us 
property expropriated by iran and for goods and services that were 
delivered but never paid for 
the big claims still outstanding involve mainly us military 
equipment for which iran contracted but did not receive after the 
overthrow of shah reza pahlavi iran in 1979 canceled contracts for 
9 billion in weapons including four destroyers under construction 
that were later taken over by the us navy 
the tehran government has since claimed 11 billion for 
undelivered gear 
also outstanding are claims by major us oil firms for 
properties expropriated by the revolutionary government the 
companies have put that figure at 5 billion 
still pending as well is an american offer to voluntarily 
compensate the families of persons killed in july 1988 when a us 
warship in the persian gulf shot down an iranian airbus iran has 
yet to accept the offer 
the united states is represented at the claims talks by abraham 
sofaer the state departments chief legal adviser 
dealing with major claims the tribunal earlier awarded more 
than 13 billion to american claimants and about 130 million to 
iranians the state department said 
the tribunal also has ordered the return of 492 million in 
iranian funds held in escrow after bank claims against the money 
are satisfied 
