a report made public wednesday contended that both the us and 
panamanian military violated international humanitarian law 
governing armed conflict during the us invasion of panama five 
months ago 
the study was prepared by americas watch which attempts to 
promote protection of human rights in latin america and the 
caribbean 
some 15000 persons were left homeless in the attack and a 
very rough estimate is that 5070 civilians were killed the 
study said many more were seriously wounded 
the attack took place on the panama defense force headquarters 
situated in the midst of a poor panamanian neighborhood called el 
chorrillo 
the report gave little credence to allegations by some observers 
that forces loyal to panamanian gen manuel antonio noriega were 
responsible for fires that broke out in el chorrillo and left 
numerous civilian casualties 
noriega was ousted by the invading force and subsequently was 
flown to the united states for trial on drugtrafficking charges 
the study said us military leaders were unable to cite 
military necessity such as the need for surprise as a reason for 
not informing the residents of el chorrillo that an attack on the 
headquarters was imminent 
there was no immediate comment on the report from the pentagon 
in contrast to the americas watch report roman catholic priests 
