two california democrats battling for their 
partys gubernatorial nomination have been trading the lead almost 
as often as pollsters can crank out new numbers 
the race between former san francisco mayor dianne feinstein and 
state attorney general john van de kamp may well be decided by two 
onehour debates set for statewide broadcast on sunday and one week 
later 
with less than one month to go before the states june 5 
primary the candidates have had few facetoface encounters and 
the campaign largely has been a fundraising fight and a battle of 
television ads 
these campaigns have become a black box said darry sragow 
feinsteins campaign manager on one side you put in dollar 
bills and on the other side you run out video tape 
total spending for the governors race is expected to reach 18 
million to 20 million by november 
the democratic contest has been marked by sharp shifts in public 
opinion feinstein was well ahead of van de kamp in early polls 
but the next round of surveys showed her lagging behind by a 
seemingly insurmountable doubledigit deficit 
next a milliondollar media blitz that extolled feinsteins 
performance as mayor of san francisco and cast her as a takecharge 
executive moved her from 18 percentage points behind van de kamp to 
19 ahead in six weeks 
