<TEXT>
the countrys secondlargest political 
party has asked parliament to declare its intention to leave the 
warsaw pact and become a neutral nation 
the proposal made wednesday by the league of free democrats 
advocates making it clear that hungary does not wish to belong to 
either the warsaw pact or nato 
it is similar to a 1956 government statement that annulled 
hungarys membership in the sovietled military alliance and 
prompted the soviet invasion that crushed a nationalist uprising 
deputy parliament speaker matyas szueroes said the proposal 
would be discussed during the next session of the new parliament 
which was chosen in march and april in the countrys first free 
elections in four decades 
the liberal free democrats led by former dissidents won 94 of 
parliaments 394 seats in the balloting the largest party the 
centerright hungarian democratic forum won 165 seats and is 
trying to form a coalition government with smaller traditional 
parties 
the socialist party which is dominated by former members of the 
longruling communist party won 33 seats 
the free democrats have not been approached as coalition 
partners and it is unclear if a new government would adopt their 
proposal 
the party campaigned on a platform of swift transfer to a free 
market economy while the democratic forum emphasized the need to 
avoid social disruption and generally emphasizes conservative 
traditional values 
hungarys leadership has until now pledged to remain in the 
sovietled alliance although individual leaders have repeatedly 
suggested the country could one day become neutral 
the free democrats proposed the new move on the basis of the 
1956 statement 
the proposal was presented by miklos vasarhelyi an associate of 
imre nagy the leader of the 1956 uprising vasarhelyi was 
imprisoned following the uprising nagy was executed after a show 
trial 
three days after hungary declared its withdrawal from the warsaw 
pact soviet troops and tanks rolled into budapest they have since 
remained though hungary has negotiated the complete withdrawal of 
soviet troops from its territory by the middle of next year 
the new parliament has asked to renegotiate the accord to 
provide for a quicker withdrawal 
a special subcommittee of the foreign relations committee in 
parliament is examining the issue 
vasarhelyi said the proposal does not call for hungarys 
immediate withdrawal from the warsaw pact but opens negotiations on 
the topic with moscow 
but he said that if the proposal is adopted hungary should 
suspend all activity in the east bloc alliance and forbid warsaw 
pact exercises on its soil 
the warsaw pact was established in 1955 and includes the soviet 
union east germany poland czechslovakia hungary romania and 
bulgaria the alliances future is uncertain now that most of its 
members have virtually broken free of soviet domination 
