<TEXT>
sen dave durenberger faces new ethics charges 
that he abused his office and misused senate money in a pattern 
of improper conduct involving his minneapolis condominium 
the senate ethics committee on wednesday widened its case 
against the minnesota republican by finding substantial credible 
evidence of financial wrongdoing misrepresentations to the 
senate and improper administration of his blind trust 
the latest allegations stem from senate expense payments that 
durenberger claimed for renting the residence that he partly owned 
for several years durenberger may have violated federal law as 
well as senate rules the committee said 
the latest charges were added to an earlier list of allegations 
that will be the subject of triallike committee hearings scheduled 
to begin june 12 
the committee last february charged durenberger with six 
possible rules violations stemming from a 100000 book promotion 
deal and acceptance of free limousine service for personal travel 
the new allegations are the first mention in the case of 
durenbergers blind trust which had been approved by the ethics 
committee in february 1986 
durenbergers chief of staff bert mckasy said the trust held 
the senators interest in the condominium partnership 
the question as we understand it is whether the trustee of a 
trust who is also the senators attorney and the senator should 
have discussed the sale of the condominium and related matters 
mckasy said 
the committee listed three other possible violations 
submitting misleading travel reimbursement vouchers to the 
senate 
misrepresenting the ownership of the condominium 
backdating real estate transactions and other documents through 
which durenberger transferred the property to a partnership in 1984 
the panel found substantial cause to conclude that 
durenberger may have abused his united states senate office and 
misused united states senate funds through a pattern of improper 
conduct which has brought discredit upon the united states senate 
this is the logical next step in the inquiry said 
durenbergers press secretary lois west its what we expected 
would happen 
durenberger has denied any wrongdoing in the condominium deal 
although he admitted he was trying to cut the expense of 
maintaining homes in both the washington area and minnesota 
durenberger transferred the condominium to a partnership in 
which he was a partner in 1984 and backdated papers to obtain 
reimbursement for staying there in 1983 according to documents he 
provided the senate rules committee 
he sold the property to a company owned by his former campaign 
manager in 1987 but continued to get reimbursed for staying there 
until late last year 
durenberger repaid the senate 11005 last january after the 
rules committee decided he was not entitled to expenses incurred 
when he stayed at the condominium during official congressional 
recesses 
he also used the condominium when he returned to minnesota on 
weekends and at other times when the senate was in session 
durenbergers aides claim the backdating was proper since the 
senator had made the agreement for the partnership at that time 
durenberger said last week that he had been negotiating 
informally with the ethics committee and that the hearing date 
served as a deadline for reaching a settlement if he negotiated a 
plea agreement by then the hearings would be unnecessary 
mckasy said the committees statement makes clear that all 
matters will be resolved together in the near future 
durenberger does not face reelection until 1994 but polls 
indicate he has lost significant support in minnesota because of 
the yearold ethics investigation 
four of the six counts approved against durenberger on feb 22 
result from an arrangement he had with a publisher to promote two 
books he had written a fifth count charged durenberger with 
accepting gifts of limousine service for personal trips in the 
boston area 
the sixth count alleged that durenbergers actions reflected 
poorly on the senate 
