<TEXT>
the senate is moving toward passing a bill to 
loosen a ban on political campaigning by federal employees as 
republican opponents bowed to repeated defeats on amendments and 
agreed to allow a final vote 
under an agreement reached late wednesday between the two 
parties leaders democrat george mitchell of maine and republican 
bob dole of kansas the senate would vote on a wholesale revision 
of the 1939 hatch act before recessing tonight 
before the final vote minority republicans will have the 
opportunity to offer nine more amendments including a measure by 
dole to continue the current restrictions on employees in 
intelligence agencies the justice department the internal revenue 
service and the federal election commission 
a similar amendment by dole was defeated on a 5146 vote tuesday 
despite a veto threat by president bush the bill was 
overwhelmingly approved by the house a year ago and in several 
test votes this week and last several republican senators joined 
democrats in defeating amendments by dole and other gop leaders 
aimed at retaining most of the current restrictions 
some 29 million federal civil service and postal workers are 
now prohibited entirely from working in campaigns soliciting 
contributions and holding office in the political parties or 
attending their state and national conventions as delegates 
even holding a campaign placard at a rally or voting in local 
caucuses on party nominations is a hatch act violation for which a 
federal employee can be suspended from his or her job 
the unionendorsed bill would still prohibit federal workers 
from engaging in any political activities while on the job and 
continue to bar them from running for public office or soliciting 
campaign contributions from the public 
but they could start holding office in local state and national 
political organizations and for the first time solicit campaign 
funds from the coworkers on behalf of candidates or federal 
employee union political action committees 
dole called the bill a pot of gold for the democrats because 
they receive on average about 90 percent of the millions of 
dollars in pac contributions already raised by postal and federal 
employee unions 
democrats have repeatedly denied an ulterior motive saying they 
only want to give federal workers the same political rights that 
people in eastern europe are beginning to exert 
bushs senior advisers have said they would urge him to veto any 
change in the law as undermining the integrity and independence 
of the traditionally nonpartisan civil service 
the senate has spent more than a week on the legislation with 
democrats mustering between a dozen and 17 republican votes on each 
of the challenging amendments by gop leaders 
george gould a lobbyist for the national association of letter 
carriers called the stream of amendments an attempt by gop leaders 
to slow the process to give the white house time to try to peel 
away votes 
republican whip alan simpson of wyoming admitted his party 
lacked the 40 votes needed to maintain a filibuster against the 
bill in the 100member senate he said the real test will come 
later when the white house asks republican leaders to scrape 
together the 34 votes needed to sustain a veto by bush 
in bushs first 16 months in office congressional democrats 
have been unable in 10 attempts to override any of his vetoes 
