<TEXT>
a federal judge in a decision with 
farreaching consequences has ruled northern wisconsins 
harvestable natural resources should be split 5050 between 
chippewas and nonindians 
the ruling wednesday by us district judge barbara crabb came 
in a lawsuit over chippewa rights under 19th century treaties to 
hunt deer but state legal experts say the decision extends to 
fishing and logging 
lawyers for wisconsins estimated 4000 chippewas had no 
immediate comment on the ruling 
tom maulson a chippewa active in treaty issues said the tribe 
has supported the idea of sharing resources for years he said 
dividing the resources will not unfairly deprive the chippewa of 
their rights 
i bet the tribe will never touch 50 percent he said we 
say the resource is for everybody maybe theyll start to realize 
thats what weve wanted all along 
the ruling came in a case that began with the arrest of two 
chippewas in 1974 for ice fishing off the reservation 
mrs crabb wrote that equal sharing is the fairest result and 
the inevitable one whatever analysis is employed 
she said the indians needs for a moderate standard of living 
dictate their right to a full share of the harvest subject to a 
ceiling set at 50 percent to prevent the frustration of the 
nonindian treaty right 
previously mrs crabb had ruled the chippewa are entitled to 100 
percent of the safe allowable catch of fish an allowance the 
indians had never come close to reaching state lawyers said the 
new ruling alters the previous one 
its our understanding of this decision that it does not apply 
only to deer but that it applies to all natural resources said 
wisconsin attorney general donald hanaway it includes fish it 
includes furbearing animals white tail deer and timber 
under treaties ceding indian territory to the us government 
wisconsins chippewas retain the right to spear fish hunt and cut 
timber off the reservation on 23929 square miles of public land in 
northern wisconsin 
since a court affirmed those rights in 1983 the chippewa have 
encountered huge and sometimes violent protests by nonindians who 
claim the treaty rights give them an unfair edge and threaten to 
deplete fish and timber 
the chippewa have filed a series of lawsuits asking the court to 
define how much of the resources they are entitled to and to what 
degree the state can regulate tribal activities 
state and tribal officials said that the chippewa were unlikely 
to take 50 percent of the available deer and that the ruling could 
provide a model for resolving the dispute over the tribes rights 
dean crist spokesman for the antitreaty rights group stop 
treaty abuse said that mrs crabbs ruling was a good step that 
didnt go far enough 
the bad thing is you still have less than 1 percent of the 
population with 50 percent of the resource he said it looks 
to me like shes trying to courtappoint comanagement 
comanagement the sharing of resources that has been used 
successfully in washington state has been touted by some as a 
solution to wisconsins dispute 
still to be decided are possible financial payments to the 
tribes for alleged state infringment on treaty rights 
