<TEXT>
the mississippi delta region the nations 
poorest has plenty of reserves of hope and could become vital 
given enough assistance a federal commission says 
the ninemember delta commission conducted an 18month study of 
219 of the poorest counties and parishes of tennessee illinois 
missouri kentucky arkansas mississippi and louisiana 
these are people who prefer hope to despair this is a region 
that given the right tools and knowledge can help the nation as a 
whole strike a new balance of competitiveness in a global 
economy the reports summary said 
the commercial appeal of memphis obtained a draft of the 
commissions report which was to be presented monday to the white 
house 
sen dale bumpers dark who proposed creating the commission 
two years ago questioned where the money to back its plans would 
come from 
the federal government and the states and the cities are all 
in a terrible fiscal crisis bumpers said this week 
the draft report calls for a delta development bank a delta 
common market a memphisbased agricultural technology center 
conventions of delta religious leaders and multistate economic 
planning 
it seeks federal and state aid with a strong emphasis on 
volunteerism to improve education highways ports health care 
and race relations for the region in which 83 million people live 
arkansas gov bill clinton the commission chairman wrote in a 
letter accompanying the draft that it is a handbook for action 
not simply another government study 
this is not a report that will collect dust it is very 
practical and it can be used by a wide variety of groups and 
individuals said mississippi gov ray mabus a panel member 
the panel did not put price tags on its recommendations and 
cautions that there are no quick fixes 
not only must the federal government find new ways to invest 
in the lower mississippi deltas future but other levels of 
government the private sector civic and nonprofit organizations 
must step forward the report said 
area lawmakers have all but ruled out chances for creation of a 
largely federally funded agency such as the appalachian regional 
commission 
the report recommends creation of an interim statefunded 
advocacy group to follow up on findings after the panel dissolves 
the draft leaves to congress to decide what permanent body would 
monitor delta progress 
the reports recommendations include 
seeking federal funds to start a model magnet school in each 
delta state 
asking area colleges to establish a delta higher education 
association to focus research on area development needs in 
aquaculture wood alternative fuels and clean coal 
designating the region as a national laboratory for 
seeking new ways to improve race relations 
creating an agency to promote regional tourism 
starting annual meetings of each states religious leaders 
including a deltawide meeting every two years to mobilize 
volunteer efforts 
designating acquaculture catfish shrimp and crawfish 
farming as fullfledged agricultural commodities in the 1990 farm 
bill 
providing an additional 400000 units of housing for 
lowincome delta residents by 2001 
improving major roads in the region 
expanding volunteers in service to america vista by 
promising financial incentives to volunteers who work in the 
region 
the other panel members are louisiana gov buddy roemer ed 
jones a retired congressman from tennessee kentucky local 
government commissioner lee troutwine missouri agriculture 
department director charles kruse rhonda vinson of southern 
illinois university webb franklin a former congressman from 
greenwood miss and john shepherd a st louis lawyer 
