sugar is the latest scarcity a shop in sofias downtown 
rakowski street selling several hundred pounds of imported sugar 
was besieged by hundreds of citizens on monday and tuesday 
lukanov said draft legislation on privatizing farmland and 
industry will be published for public debate within the next 
few days currently farmers are allowed to own only small plots of 
about 1 acres around their homes with the bulk of agricultural 
land in state hands 
lukanov also disclosed that bulgarian geologists had discovered 
rich oil fields in central northern bulgaria around the town of 
pleven 
the oil deposits are some 13000 feet deep the premier said 
bulgaria is negotiating with foreign firms to exploit the oil 
fields whose exact extent was not revealed 
bulgaria long viewed as the soviet unions most loyal ally in 
eastern europe is seeking to boost its ties to the west as it 
moves away from the hardline communist rule of todor zhivkov 
ousted november after 35 years in power 
but the ruling socialists are cautious about scrapping 
centralized economic planning and subsidies and introducing a 
totally free market 
lukanov praised an accord signed with the european community 
this week to give bulgarian goods including agricultural produce 
and greater access to the ec market he also said bulgaria hopes to 
join the international monetary fund by september 1990 
