the house voted today to guarantee workers up 
to three months of unpaid leave in family emergencies ignoring a 
white house threat to veto the bill 
the house voted 237187 to approve the bill after turning back 
opponents efforts to send it back to committee the bill now goes 
to the senate 
the bill requires business and government employers to provide 
workers with up to 12 weeks of unpaid medical leave or for the care 
of a new or ill child parent or spouse it exempts small 
businesses with fewer than 50 workers and drops earlier language 
setting various periods of leave for workers with different 
emergencies 
the vote while a victory for supporters was short of what 
would be needed to override a presidential veto though the bill 
had bipartisan support and the backing of the house democratic 
leadership more than 50 democrats voted against it 
approval came as opponents withdrew a series of amendments and 
after a 259167 vote to adopt a substitute measure sponsors said 
was a compromise aimed at drawing more support to the measure 
the bill strongly opposed by the bush administration faces an 
uncertain future in the senate the senate labor and human 
resources committee approved a similar measure more than a year 
ago but sponsors have not yet scheduled floor action and none is 
expected before memorial day 
supporters of the measure pointed to president bushs own 
