<TEXT>
the united states and its nato allies 
agreed today there is a diminishing need for battlefield 
nuclear weapons in its alliance arsenal given the recent political 
changes in eastern europe 
nato also welcomed the prospect of early negotiations with the 
soviet union on cutting shortrange nuclear missile forces 
the 14 defense ministers of the natos nuclear planning group 
also called on the soviet union to make substantial reductions 
unilaterally in its shortrange nuclear missile systems 
the statement came as the group wrapped up its twoday session 
in kananaskis at a rocky mountain ski resort 
the alliances statement follows president bushs recent 
decision to cancel the development of new tactical nuclear missiles 
and artillery systems designed for deployment by the nato allies 
the alliance statement did not address calls by the dutch and 
west germans for unilateral nato withdrawal of its hundreds of 
aging nuclear artillery shells which are designed to be shot on 
european battlefields at very close range in the event of an 
overwhelming warsaw pact conventional attack 
given the political and military changes now taking place in 
central and eastern europe together with the prospect of early 
signature and implementation of a conventional forces in europe 
treaty we agreed that there is a diminishing need for nuclear 
systems of the shortest range it said 
the alliance ministers welcomed bushs decision to cancel the 
planned update of nuclear weaponry and said it demonstrates once 
again the ability of the alliance to take the initiative in a 
rapidly changing situation 
the alliance ministers said they welcomed the prospect of 
early negotiations between the united states and the soviet union 
on shortrange nuclear missile systems and emphasized the 
importance of consultation within the alliance on the development 
of objectives for these negotiations 
while the alliance members agreed on the need to cut natos 
shortrange nuclear arsenal they left decisions on how deep those 
reductions should be to the leaders of the nato summit nations who 
will meet in london in early july 
the alliance ministers said that they recognized that a 
lessening need for shortrange nuclear weapons means relatively 
greater importance on substrategic nuclear weapons that offer 
both flexibility and longer range 
this appeared to be a reference to an alliance interest to shift 
a greater reliance on airlaunched nuclear weapons which are 
already based in europe and slated for upgrading sometime during 
this decade 
the ministers said they wanted their aides as well to step up 
work on a lengthy study of how to best reduce the alliances 
nuclear stockpile amid the rapidly changing political and military 
environment in europe 
it was the pacts first evaluation of its nuclear weapons 
strategy since the dramatic upheavals in eastern europe and the 
withering of their oncestrong adversary the warsaw pact 
there is scope for reductions britains defense chief tom 
king said of the tactical nuclear weapons i think there is 
general agreement on that 
there are some 1600 aging nucleartipped artillery shells based 
in west germany greece italy the netherlands and turkey they 
are designed to be shot at very close range to halt an overwhelming 
advance of warsaw pact tanks and other conventional forces 
it isnt known how many shortrange artillery shells the soviets 
possess generally the soviets have relied more on missiles in 
their tactical arsenal 
but with the recent prodemocracy revolutions in eastern europe 
and the steps being taken toward german unification the artillery 
is seen as increasingly irrelevant to some nato governments and 
their constituents 
</TEXT>
