<TEXT>
the united states may be mortgaging its future 
defenses by not limiting collaboration with allied nations in 
hightech weapons development according to a congressional study 
released thursday 
such collaboration makes business sense for the companies 
involved but may ultimately make the united states too dependent on 
foreign suppliers and erode parts of the us defense industrial 
base said the study by the office of technology assessment a 
nonpartisan analytical agency of the congress 
more joint weapons projects with european or japanese companies 
will mean less business for all but the largest american defense 
companies the study said 
the united states could end up with a defense industrial 
structure inadequate for the defense of the nation it said 
the study added on the other hand that erosion of us defense 
industries may not be a security risk because the united states may 
need less weaponmaking capacity as the cold war winds down and 
eastwest arms cuts are implemented 
even so the trend toward greater useuropean collaboration is 
casting doubt on americas longheld commitment to global 
superiority in weapons technology the study said traditionally 
the united states has kept this edge by focusing on military 
applications for new technologies with little regard for possible 
civilian uses 
now as defense industry competition heats up in the postcold 
war period the focus of multinational defense collaboration will 
be on dualuse technologies it said 
this might ultimately undermine the position of the united 
states as a military superpower because dualuse technologies 
would be available to many nations the study said in time 
the us military position might degenerate to the status of first 
among equals 
the study quoted an unidentified highranking military officer 
as saying if we want to stay a superpower we will invest to be 
ahead of the world in nextgeneration systems otherwise we 
are codeveloping and therefore not leading we lose the superpower 
label 
sen jeff bingaman dnm chairman of the armed services 
subcommittee on defense industry and technology took a different 
view saying more us emphasis on dualuse technologies would help 
the domestic industry survive leaner times 
in light of the declining defense budgets of the 1990s we may 
need to concentrate more of our cooperation both with our european 
allies and especially with japan on dualuse technology rather 
than fullscale weapons systems he said 
</TEXT>
