<DOCNO> AP900510-0122 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
student financial aid provided by private 
colleges to attract lowincome and minority students more than 
doubled from 1970 to 1987 an association of the schools said 
thursday 
but richard rosser president of the national institute of 
independent colleges and universities said such aid cannot 
continue to grow at that pace without the colleges jeopardizing 
their own financial health and commitments to other areas of 
need 
an institute study entitled a commitment to access said 
that independent colleges and universities provided 234 billion 
from their own resources for financial assistance to undergraduate 
students in the 198788 school year a 102 percent increase 
adjusted for inflation over 197071 
the federal governments commitment to providing student 
financial assistance especially in the form of grants must be 
strengthened if lowincome and middleincome students are going to 
be allowed the choice of an education best suited for them the 
independent sector cannot do it alone he said 
more than threequarters of the growth occurred since the 
198081 school year the study said estimating that the figure 
reached 2626 billion in 198889 
in the 197576 school year federal aid was almost 3 times the 
aid provided by the institutions themselves rosser said adding 
that independent colleges and universities now provide more grant 
assistance to undergraduates than all federal student aid grants 
combined 
federal aid he said now focuses on the truly needy with 
little help for students from middleclass families the schools 
also provide little aid to middleclass students 
more than 85 percent of the aid provided by private colleges in 
198788 2 billion was awarded as grants and scholarships other 
aid was offered as loans and workstudy grants 
in the 198687 term expenses for a typical privatecollege 
student receiving aid averaged 10300 for tuition fees room and 
board an average of 7300 was provided in financial aid grants 
loans and workstudy leaving the student outofpocket expenses of 
about 3000 
the study said that on average 59 percent of all undergraduates 
attending independent colleges and universities received some form 
of institutionally provided aid in 198788 up from 44 percentin 
197071 
to finance increased student aid rosser said private colleges 
are often forced to keep faculty salaries low defer maintenance 
and cut back on purchases of library material and science equipment 
</TEXT>
