<TEXT>
foreigners continue to own just under 1 
percent of the nations agricultural land a level that has varied 
little over the years the agriculture department said thursday 
the departments economic research service made its 1989 
yearend review of reports under a 1978 law requiring foreigners to 
register us agricultural land holdings 
as of dec 31 1989 about 129 million acres of agricultural 
land were owned by foreigners an increase of 263273 acres from a 
year earlier 
foreign ownership of us agricultural land remained 
relatively steady from 1981 through 1989 slightly above or below 1 
percent of the privately owned agricultural land in the united 
states said john lee administrator of the agency 
of the land owned by foreign interests 46 percent was forest 
land 18 percent cropland 31 percent pasture and other 
agricultural land and 5 percent agricultural land not under 
cultivation 
corporations both us and foreign owned 81 percent of the 
foreignheld acreage partnerships 10 percent and individuals 7 
percent the remainder is held by estates trusts associations 
institutions and others 
japanese investors owned 2 percent of the foreignheld acreage 
while about 73 percent of the total was owned by investors from 
canada britain west germany france the netherlands antilles 
switzerland and the netherlands the report said 
maine continued to have the heaviest concentration of foreign 
ownership with holdings of almost 21 million acres 
the report said that 93 percent of the foreignowned acreage 
will remain in agricultural production according to its owners 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900510-0134 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the worst cyclone to hit india in more 
than a decade moved inland thursday killing at least 85 people and 
leaving hundreds of homes flattened and more than 90 villages under 
water 
the storm first began bashing indias southeastern coast with 
heavy rains and tidal surges tuesday and it made landfall 
wednesday evening hitting coastal districts along the bay of bengal 
with winds up to 155 mph 
by late thursday the storm lay over the inland town of 
bhadrachalam about 105 miles north of the coast wind speeds were 
decreasing as the cyclones fury weakened said officials in 
hyderabad the capital of andrha pradesh state 
united news of india said winds of 70 to 80 mph would continue 
for another three days as the storm moved inland 
the weather office said the storm was likely to move north and 
weaken gradually but that lowlying heavily populated coastal 
regions would continue to receive much rain 
tv and radio reports said the storm killed 57 people but local 
officials reported a higher death toll saying at least 75 people 
died in andrha pradesh and 10 more in neighboring tamil nadu state 
the death toll was expected to rise as rescue workers reached 
isolated villages 
the officials who spoke on condition of anonymity said at 
least 2 million people in four districts of andrha pradesh state 
were affected by the cyclone 
tens of thousands of people were cut off from rescue workers as 
the heavy rains and towering waves left at least 90 villages under 
water the staterun television said the storm dumped more than 16 
inches of water on the coastal regions 
but late thursday rescue workers did manage to reach the 
lowlying coastal village of yedurumudi where about 7000 
residents had been marooned by the storm officials said they said 
it was a miracle that residents were not too badly affected by the 
storm 
indian news reports said residents there rejected an evacuation 
order because the village was not affected by a 1977 cyclone which 
killed more than 10000 people in southern india 
officials said casualties from the current storm were relatively 
low because early warnings gave authorities time to evacuate more 
than 150000 people from the coastal districts in 1977 few people 
were evacuated 
as the storm struck the coast the high winds and waves up to 33 
feet knocked down hundreds of thatched huts and uprooted thousands 
of trees 
residents who left the coastal town of machilipatnam which bore 
the brunt of the cyclone said the streets were waistdeep in water 
one resident who escaped to hyderabad said it rained 
continuously for 20 hours in machilipatnam 
united news of india said thousands of houses were damaged by 
gales and heavy rains that lashed the area before and during the 
cyclone many towns and villages were plunged into darkness as 
electricity lines were downed and several power stations severely 
damaged it said trains stopped running 
the news agency quoted officials as saying about 100 telephone 
exchanges were damaged disrupting telecommunications and the 
roads were littered with fallen trees 
the hardesthit districts comprising a small peninsula that 
juts out into the bay of bengal were krishna east godavari and 
west godavari united news said adding that more than 400000 
people were affected in east godavari alone 
the highest casualties were in krishna district where 24 people 
were killed the news agency said at least 33 others died in other 
parts of the state it said 
most of the deaths in andhra pradesh occurred when walls 
collapsed or when flood waters swept people away 
cyclones are the indian oceans equivalent of hurricanes they 
usually come in the spring just before the monsoon season begins 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

