<TEXT>
the united states is recalling its ambassador 
to romania as a signal of displeasure over intimidation and 
harassment of opposition parties the state department said 
thursday 
the recall of ambassador alan green was based on reports of 
irregularities in the romanian electoral process which raise 
questions about whether those elections will be free and fair 
spokeswoman margaret tutwiler said 
she said green will return to bucharest in time for the may 20 
elections when romanians will vote for a president and a bicameral 
parliament 
anticommunist demonstrators in romania contend the elections 
are being manipulated by the interim government in a way that could 
lead to domination by communists previously associated with the 
regime of the late president nicolae ceausescu 
government leaders maintain that they were for the most part 
dissidents who suffered under ceausescus rule 
ms tutiler said we have urged the interim romanian 
government to take more vigorous steps to maintain order and to 
protect the rights of all candidates in these elections 
among the electoral problems she cited were the incidence of 
organized acts of intimidation and harassment directed against 
some opposition parties and candidates 
we are also concerned about complaints that several major 
parties still encounter obstacles in obtaining their fair share of 
broadcast time on the publicly controlled radio and television and 
in distributing their campaign literature through the mail as well 
as problems with distributing independent newspapers ms 
tutwiler said 
she said a fair election is crucial to the further 
democratization in romania and to good relations with the united 
states 
the international human rights law group a private research 
organization issued a report expressing concerns similar to those 
of the state department 
the report said there is widespread apprehension throughout 
romania that the national salvation front which dominates the 
interim government has unfair advantages over other parties 
a law group delegation which visited romania in april said it 
could not judge the truth of the allegations but the belief that 
these advantages exist is pervasive and has created deep resentment 
in many sectors of the population the report said 
if the allegations are not promptly addressed it said there 
is a risk that the election process will be regarded by substantial 
segments of the politically active population as not being free and 
fair and therefore that the legitimacy of the elected government 
will be questioned 
