nelson mandela arrived thursday for his 
first visit to angola and thanked the marxist government and its 
allies for supporting his african national congress in its struggle 
against whiteminority rule in south africa 
mandela in an emotional speech to tens of thousands of angolans 
packing luandas dusty may 1 square said i pay tribute to 
comrade president jose eduardo dos santos his government and the 
angolan people for all the help they have given us 
the progress we have made in our struggle is owed largely to 
angola and we hope that one day we will be as free as you said 
mandela 
mandela shielded from the blazing midday sun by an umbrella 
also praised cuban president fidel castro and soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachev for helping independence movements in southern 
africa 
he described cuba as a poor country economically but said 
theres one thing where that country stands out head and 
shoulders above the rest that is in its love for human rights and 
liberty 
he said he hoped to visit havana and moscow soon 
last week the anc agreed in principle with south african 
president fw de klerk to seek a peaceful end to apartheid and 
minority rule in south africa 
but mandelas speech in luanda mixed optimism for peace with 
revolutionary rhetoric more reminiscent of the battle cries of the 
mid1970s when angola became host to at least seven major anc 
military training bases 
angolas prominent military and logistic aid to the movement 
ended in 1988 as part of a regional peace accord with south africa 
and cuba 
those usbrokered agreements also set terms for namibian 
independence the withdrawal of some 50000 cuban troops from 
angola and the end of south african support to unita rebels 
fighting angolas government 
according to mandela the anc has noted the moves afoot to 
bring about peace in angola and we support those moves 
heavy sustained applause from the crowd followed his words 
we are distressed that such a great and beautiful country is 
split from top to bottom by a civil war that has been engineered by 
south africa and other hostile powers said mandela 
he promised unspecified anc support for the angolan government 
south african troops fought alongside unita in the field against 
angolan government forces and their cuban allies from 1975 
dos santos claimed thursday that former south african president 
pieter botha offered to cease aid to unita if luanda agreed to halt 
support for the south west african peoples organization it 
recently won namibias independence elections 
south african aid to unita formally stopped with the new york 
accords but luanda recently renewed accusations that assistance 
from pretoria is still reaching the rebels the rebels also receive 
a reported 50 million in us aid 
