<TEXT>
prime minister toshiki kaifu on thursday urged a 
radical revision of the electoral system saying it is the only way 
to reduce the power of money in japanese politics 
it is clear to me that the public wants clean 
easytounderstand politics kaifu said in a nationally televised 
news conference i will bet the fate of my administration on 
achieving this reform 
kaifu endorsed the recommendations of an advisory council to 
change japans system of multipleseat constituencies reduce 
politicians ability to raise money on their own and tighten rules 
on reporting political donations 
looking back on the recruit influencepeddling scandal it 
is the central theme of my administration to clear political 
distrust and shift elections from a race of individuals to one of 
political parties he said 
kaifu 59 came to office in august after two predecessors 
resigned in quick succession over the recruit and sex scandals 
recruit co a giant in the information industry made lavish 
donations and questionable stock sales to leading politicians 
businessmen and bureaucrats 
initially seen as a stopgap prime minister because he lacked a 
power base within the governing liberal democratic party kaifu has 
gained public support with his clean image and efforts to ease 
usjapan trade friction 
analysts express skepticism however over the possibilities of 
drastic electoral system reforms 
while some politicians are aware that electoral reforms are 
essential to wipe out money politics it is too risky for most of 
them to accept such drastic reforms said takashi inoguchi a 
political science professor at tokyo university 
kaifu said he would consult with the opposition parties to build 
a consensus for introduction of an electoral reform bill by 
november 
japan now has 130 constituencies for elections to the 512seat 
lower house most elect three to five legislators 
to win a majority the governing party must field more than one 
candidate in each constituency 
candidates from the same party thus cannot compete on policy 
issues said isao sato a law professor at tokai university and 
cochairman of the electoral review committee 
they inevitably vie for popularity by spending lavishly to 
court voters sato said that not only leads to corrupt money 
politics but also reduces the significance of policy debates 
the committee formed in june proposes creating 300 singleseat 
constituencies and having 200 members elected to nationwide 
atlarge constituencies in the powerful lower house the lower 
house can override the upper house and enact legislation on its own 
the lower house proposals would limit each candidate to having 
two fundraising groups now there is no limit and require the 
reporting of donations more than 64 the current limit is 6400 
