<TEXT>
the senate brushed aside a threatened veto by 
president bush and voted thursday to allow federal civil service 
and postal workers to take a more active role in partisan politics 
on a 6730 vote after eight days of debate the senate approved 
a wholesale revision of the 1939 hatch act which prohibits 29 
million government employees from participating in political 
campaigns 
the law would still prohibit federal workers from engaging in 
political activities on the job and from running for public office 
or soliciting campaign funds from the public 
but they could in their off time hold office in local state and 
national political organizations attend political conventions as 
delegates and solicit campaign funds from coworkers on behalf of 
candidates or federal employee union political action committees 
thirteen republicans joined all 54 senate democrats in passing 
the bill despite an intensive effort by the white house to prevent 
it from garnering the 67 votes it would need to override a veto 
hopefully we can sustain a veto senate republican leader 
bob dole of kansas said before the vote congressional democrats 
have been unable to override any of bushs 10 vetoes in his first 
16 months in office 
a year ago the house passed by a vetoproof 29790 vote a 
broader bill that also would remove the prohibitions on running for 
public office and soliciting campaign funds from the public 
bushs senior advisers have said they would urge him to veto any 
change in the law as undermining the integrity and independence 
of the traditionally nonpartisan civil service 
the legislation was sought by federal employee and postal unions 
after the reagan administration filed hatch act charges against 
three union presidents for endorsing democrat walter mondale in the 
1984 presidential election 
before the final vote minority republicans tried to continue 
the current restrictions on employees of the irs intelligence 
agencies the justice department and the federal election 
commission 
certain critical agencies of this govrernment need to be 
beyond political involvement and not have any taint of 
politics or coercion said sen pete v domenici rnm 
his amendment to exempt all employees of those agencies from the 
looser restrictions on political involvement and also forbid all 
government workers from soliciting coworkers for campaign funds 
was defeated on a 5839 vote 
the senate did adopt on a 970 vote an amendment by dole that 
would maintain the current restrictions on the 240 employees of the 
federal election commission 
but republicans failed in several attempts to delete language 
from the bill that would allow federal workers to spend their off 
time soliciting campaign gifts from coworkers on behalf of union 
pacs 
dole called the provision a pot of gold for the democratic 
party citing statistics that 88 percent money raised and 
distributed by federal employee and postal union pacs in the 1988 
election went to democrats 
