<TEXT>
the three separatist baltic republics strengthened 
their solidarity thursday implementing an agricultural agreement 
that allows them to bypass moscow and weighing a plan to coordinate 
their government policies 
estonia proposed reviving a council of baltic states that was 
created in 1934 when the republics were independent it would 
include the president prime minister and foreign ministers of 
estonia latvia and lithuania said valle feldman a spokesman for 
the estonian foreign ministry 
estonian president arnold ruutel invited presidents vytautas 
landsbergis of lithuania and anatoly gorbunov of latvia to sign an 
agreement with him in tallinn on saturday they did not respond 
immediately 
the three governments also implemented an agreement for the 
direct exchange of agricultural supplies and products bypassing 
the central soviet ministries and trade organizations that usually 
handle such transactions the official soviet news agency tass 
reported 
last month the republics signed a package of agreements to 
integrate their economies and the deals are being implemented in 
stages 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev opposes immediate 
independence for the baltic republics which were forcibly annexed 
by the soviet union in 1940 
the proposed council of baltic states would further integrate 
the republics politically but would not constitute a confederation 
said leivi sher spokesman for estonias supreme council or 
parliament it could make nonbinding recommendations on the three 
governments 
so far its just an estonian proposal he said adding that 
the parliaments executive committee approved the measure 
it was unclear whether latvia and lithuania would agree to the 
proposal lithuanian spokesmen said no agreement was likely before 
the return to vilnius next week of lithuanian prime minister 
kazimiera prunskiene she was in paris as part of a tour of western 
capitals 
mrs prunskiene told reporters in paris that lithuanian 
officials want to negotiate their independence with moscow 
according to a formula proposed by french president francois 
mitterrand and west german chancellor helmut kohl they suggested 
that lithuania temporarily suspend laws implementing the 
declaration of independence enacted march 11 
the establishment of direct agricultural exchanges and the 
proposed council of baltic states signal a determination by the 
three republics to overcome kremlin opposition to their separatist 
aspirations 
the agricultural agreement which entered into effect today 
provides that each of the three ministries must have permanent 
representatives in the other baltic republics who will perform the 
functions of coordinators and assistants in joint efforts to 
resolve agricultural issues tass reported 
gorbachev imposed economic sanctions against lithuania after the 
republic declared its independence on may 4 latvia declared its 
independence after an unspecified transition period and gorbachev 
is studying that action according to latvian officials 
on tuesday estonia dropped the symbols of soviet power 
changing its flag and name invoked sections of the 1938 
constitution that declared independence and proclaimed solidarity 
with latvia and lithuania 
gorbachev has not responded to the estonian actions 
his embargo of oil and natural gas has taken its toll in 
lithuania private automobile owners in lithuania have been 
restricted to about seven gallons of gasoline per month and 
rations for the month of may already have been exhausted according 
to the unofficial postfactum information agency in moscow it said 
rations might be reduced further in june as supplies dwindle 
further 
also on thursday 
lithuanias parliament formally took control of the republics 
radio and television under soviet law the broadcasting system 
reported to both the vilnius government and moscow however 
lithuanians have effectively controlled their own broadcasting for 
some time 
shortly after declaring independence the republic ordered one 
of the three russianlanguage channels to switch to polish 
television for the benefit of the 7 percent of lithuanias 
population that is ethnically polish 
estonian prime minister edgar savisaar will meet friday with 
soviet defense minister dmitri yazov to discuss the spring military 
draft most estonian youths up for the draft took advantage of a 
new estonian law allowing them to perform alternative service at 
home to the fury of the soviet military 
the newsletter interfax an affiliate of moscow radio reported 
that 1500 young men chose alternative service and only 800 signed 
up at draft offices 
</TEXT>
