<TEXT>
a 3 million study aimed at breaking the 
grip of poverty on the mississippi delta aims to shift government 
spending from welfare to creating jobs a commission member said 
thursday 
a report on the study prepared during the past 18 months by the 
lower mississippi delta commission will be presented to congress 
on monday 
a summary of the report shows that the commission will offer 
more than 400 recommendations that include establishing a regional 
bank for loans to area businesses improving highways and schools 
upgrading regional health care and attracting more tourists the 
commercial appeal reported thursday 
the commissions study area took in 219 counties in illinois 
missouri kentucky tennessee arkansas mississippi and louisiana 
the region where 209 percent of the residents live below the 
federal poverty level is one of the poorest in the country and has 
one of the highest rates for infant deaths 
former rep ed jones a commission member from tennessee said 
he doubted the report would have many immediate practical effects 
but its benefit over the long run could be substantial 
congress will slowly try to do something about it but it 
will take time jones said from his home in yorkville the 
report is going to have to be researched by the committees that 
prepare the laws for congress a lot of it will be knocked out no 
doubt about it 
jones a democrat who represented rural northwestern tennessee 
for 29 years said the report tries to refocus government spending 
because commissioners know that new federal and state spending will 
be hard to come by 
theres no new money we know that but theres money that can 
be redirected he said thirty to 40 percent of the people in 
the delta region are on food stamps or some sort of welfare if you 
could reduce that by half look at the amount of money you would 
save 
the commission financed by a 3 million appropriation from 
congress is scheduled to disband sept 30 but the report suggests 
that states in the region create a successor organization to work 
as advocate for the delta initiatives 
not only must the federal government find new ways to invest 
in the lower mississippi deltas future but other levels of 
government the private sector civic and nonprofit organizations 
must step forward the reports summary said 
among its recommendations the report calls for a regional 
development bank and communitybased loan pools using federal 
state and private funds an agriculture center in memphis to help 
educate delta farmers on the latest farm technology the addition 
of 400000 housing units for lowincome delta residents by the year 
2001 federal funding for magnet schools in each delta state a 
residential high school specializing in math and science and an 
agency to promoting tourism throughout the region 
rep mike espy dmiss said lawmakers from the region have 
formed the lower mississippi delta congressional working group to 
press their colleagues to deal with the commissions report 
weve got to get off to a fast start espy said this is 
the road map 
