automobiles rebounded from february the government said thursday 
the federal reserve said consumer credit increased at a 
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 44 percent up from a scant 01 
percent rise in february that represented a sharp revision from 
the 57 percent rate estimated earlier reported for february and 
made the month the weakest in a year 
credit grew at a 37 percent annual rate in january rather than 
the earlier estimate of 64 percent the fed said 
with the dampening of economic growth this year consumers are 
borrowing less the first quarter annualized rate of 27 percent 
compares with 76 percent for all of 1989 and 85 percent for 1988 
economist sandra shaber of the futures group a washington 
consulting firm said the economy has been expanding for so long 
7 years that consumers have less appetite for big ticket 
items that are purchased with loans 
i think there also has been an erosion of consumer confidence 
people are worried they read in the paper that the 
unemployment rate went up or that interest rates are going up 
people pay attention she said 
automobile loans in march advanced 18 billion a 75 percent 
annual rate after falling at a 52 percent rate in february and 
advancing at only a 17 percent rate in january 
credit card debt rose by 2 billion or a 121 percent annual 
rate in march up from a 47 percent rate a month earlier 
