<TEXT>
the bush administration dropped its opposition 
to requiring double hulls on oil tankers thursday announcing 
support for a bill to require them on new vessels 
transportation secretary samuel skinner outlined the new 
administration position which calls for some exemptions to the 
requirement in a letter to a housesenate conference committee 
mulling over two versions of oil pollution legislation 
skinner previously opposed a house version of the bill that 
would mandate double hulls on all tankers within 15 years and said 
the administration preferred a senate bill which gave the secretary 
some discretion to require them on new vessels 
the oil industry complained that the costly retrofitting of 
existing tankers would take too many out of service 
the legislation was prompted by concern over last years alaskan 
oil spill from the singlehull exxon valdez which ran into a rock 
ledge in prince william sound 
opponents of mandatory double hulls have said the 10 million 
gallon exxon valdez spill probably would have occurred anyway and 
might even have been worse with a double hull because the ship 
could have capsized and lost all its cargo instead of 10 percent of 
it 
the new proposal would apply to tankers flying the us flag and 
foreign tankers serving us ports many foreignflag tankers are 
owned by us oil companies who register their ships under the 
flags of panama liberia and other flags of convenience to 
avoid us safety and wage regulations trade between us ports is 
reserved to usflagged ships 
the administration generally supports requiring double hulls 
on new construction of oceangoing tank vessels skinner said 
noting that a national academy of sciences study concluded that 
double hulls are safe and give better protection to the environment 
we believe that existing singleskin oceangoing tank vessels 
should be phased out after they are 25 years old beginning in 
the year 2000 skinner said 
he said this would give us and foreign tank owners about 10 
years to replace their older vessels 
the administration would not object to exemptions for vessels 
serving deepwater ports until 2015 he said unless an 
international standard for double hulls is adopted before then 
tank barges plying only the great lakes could also be exempted 
until 2015 skinner said 
this deadline is reasonable yet would serve as a strong 
encouragement to owners to build only doublehulled inland barges 
and great lakes tank vessels he said 
skinner said the new position was prompted by a compromise 
proposal by senators on the conference committee 
he said the administration would work with the committee to 
write a bill that will afford the greatest protection to the 
environment without disrupting oil supplies sending american 
refining jobs offshore or imposing unjustified burdens on the 
american consumer 
</TEXT>
