<TEXT>
walker percy whose deeply humane novels 
and essays made him a unique voice in american letters died of 
cancer thursday at his home he would have been 75 on monday 
percys first novel the moviegoer won him the national 
book award in 1962 and set the themes that would occupy him for his 
entire career modern malaise in the new south and the tenuous 
often outlandishly comic hope for human connection 
his best friend and fellow author shelby foote was in covington 
at the time of percys death at his home here on the banks of the 
bogue falaya river across lake pontchatrain from new orleans 
in jackson miss author eudora welty said im very grieved 
and very very hurt for all his family his friendship meant a lot 
to me and his work meant a great deal to me too 
services will be saturday at st josephs abbey near covington 
after moviegoer percys novels included the last 
gentleman 1966 love in the ruins 1971 lancelot 
1977 the second coming 1980 and the thanatos syndrome 
1987 
once described by critic alfred kazin as the satiric 
dostoyevsky of the bayou percy claimed to have been influenced 
more by the european existentialists especially kierkegaard than 
by fellow southerners he peddled his 1983 lost in the cosmos 
as the last selfhelp book and set out to explain why it is 
that man is the only alien creature as far as we know in the 
entire planet 
his other major piece of nonfiction was the message in the 
bottle 1975 essays on the philosophy of language 
percy revealed his thoughts in the mid50s as he contemplated 
his future after two failed novels it crossed my mind what if i 
did something that american writers never do which seems to be the 
custom in france namely that when someone writes about ideas 
they can translate the same ideas to fiction and plays so it 
just occurred to me why not take these ideas id been trying to 
write about in psychiatry and philosophy and translate them into 
a fictional setting in new orleans where i was living 
all six of his novels send uppermiddleclass southern heroes 
out in hot pursuit of those ideas 
born in birmingham ala percy was 11 when his lawyer father 
killed himself two years later his mother was killed in an 
automobile accident he and his two brothers went to greenville 
miss to live with uncle will william alexander percy his 
fathers cousin 
uncle will was the author of lanterns on the levee the 
classic treatise on the best of the old south a famed world war i 
infantry officer poet politician lawyer and planter he 
presided over a bachelor household that was a teeming crossroads of 
southern culture it was visited regularly by other poets 
politicians psychiatrists sociologists black preachers folk 
singers itinerant harmonica players percy has written the 
young ward found him the most extraordinary man i have ever 
known 
percy graduated from university of north carolina in chemistry 
and got a medical degree from columbia university in 1941 the next 
year working as a pathologist at bellevue hospital in new york 
city he caught pulmonary tuberculosis while performing autopsies 
on derelicts 
ive often said that getting a light case of tb was the best 
thing that couldve happened to me it gave me a period of enforced 
idleness said percy who spent his three years of recovery 
reading voraciously 
by the time he was well he had turned to a life of writing 
inheritance allowed him to move to new orleans and marry he 
converted to roman catholicism in 1950 he settled in covington 
with uncle wills desk in his study he raised two daughters and 
became a grandfather 
between his recovery and the publication of the moviegoer 
are 20 years that percy joked about not remembering what he did 
with 
during those apprentice years he wrote two failed novels and 
numerous articles on language and psychiatry i felt more at 
home on the psychiatric ward than anywhere else maybe it takes 
one to know one 
both his religious conversion and three years of freudian 
psychoanalysis during medical school played an integral role in his 
writing one books subtitle is the adventures of a bad catholic 
at a time near the end of the world percy won the prestigious 
campion award in 1986 from the catholic book club despite 
downplaying the role of the church in his work 
he insisted he was not a catholic writer except that his writing 
is informed by the judeochristian view of man but thats about 
it 
named by pope john paul ii as the only american on the 
pontifical council for culture percy said i understand it only 
requires one trip a year to rome i do well just to get to new 
orleans 
the seclusion of covington served him well he often gave credit 
to his original presbyterian work ethic for the discipline and 
steadiness he brought to his work mornings by the bayou he wrote 
lefthanded in a threering binder afternoons he often typed 
what hed written he said he had no terrors he had no writers 
block 
but he found it hard work he could describe the maddening 
frustration he claimed no secrets or solutions he told one 
interviewer its a question of being so pitiful god takes pity 
on you looks down and says hes done for lets let him have a 
couple of good sentences 
its a strange abject littleunderstood profession 
he is survived by his wife mary bernice two daughters mary 
pratt and ann boyd and four grandsons 
</TEXT>
