the united states france and britain have 
asked the soviet union to allow more air travel to and from berlin 
a us spokesman said thursday 
the four world war ii allies still retain control over air 
travel in the oncedivided city the western powers for several 
years have been urging more access to boost berlins status 
in view of the significant changes in and around berlin in 
recent months the allies believe that greater aviation access and 
greater coordination among berlins aviation authorities can and 
should be achieved said a statement from anthony w sariti 
spokesman for the us mission in west berlin 
it continued even prior to unification the four powers can 
work constructively with the two german states for greatly 
improving berlins aviation links 
the statement said representatives from france britain and the 
united states presented the proposals during a meeting with 
officials from the soviet embassy on thursday 
in addition to possible objections from the soviets the 
proposals for more air traffic are likely to run into difficulties 
with german environmental groups 
ecologists say berlins skies are already overcrowded with 
commercial airliners and have urged more use of rail travel 
