<TEXT>
lake eufaula the reservoir some call a 
gentle giant has turned into a menace as farmers and residents 
hundreds of miles away in arkansas battle floods unleashed from the 
lake because of heavy rains 
but us army corps of engineers officials criticized about the 
timing of the release of water from reservoirs are standing their 
ground were it not for reservoirs like eufaula on the arkansas 
river and lake texoma on the red river the flooding downstream 
could have been much worse they say 
decisions made by the corps on how fast to release water from 
the reservoirs it manages can have a crucial effect on who is 
flooded and how severely a tooearly release of water through the 
dams floodgates after a heavy rain increases flooding downstream 
while slower release can mean more flooding upstream if the 
reservoir fills up 
questions about the management of the reservoirs was raised anew 
wednesday when arkansas gov bill clinton met with a group of angry 
farmers and agreed with a suggestion that a study of corps efforts 
to control red river floodwaters might be in order 
but in the main said corps spokesman ross adkins the 
reservoirs have done their job this past week 
our projects operated as they were designed to we managed 
them just exactly as they were designed to operate said adkins 
what we do is capture all the water we can to minimize any 
damages downstream when mother nature dumps as much rain as we had 
the reservoirs took off a heck of a big bump that could have 
gone downstream 
if we had not been here a lot more houses and perhaps lives 
would have been lost he said 
the flooding on the trinity red and arkansas rivers was touched 
off by severe storms last week some areas of eastern oklahoma 
already saturated from a wet spring had as much as 12 inches of 
rain 
thirteen deaths were blamed on the storm most of them in texas 
marilyn quayle wife of vice president dan quayle toured 
hardhit south dallas on thursday she backed proposals to extend 
levees that protect the hardhit rochester park neighborhood 
you will be in our prayers mrs quayle told residents whose 
homes are still underwater 
complete damage figures for the region were not yet compiled 
but the red cross says as many as 600 homes in oklahoma may have 
been damaged by the flooding in texas estimated damage to 
agricultural production stands at 500 million and 700 million 
a disaster declaration was expanded thursday to cover nine north 
texas counties sixteen counties had already been declared disaster 
areas an action that leads to federal assistance and lowinterest 
loans for repairs 
in arkansas preliminary figures from six counties and one 
metropolitan area show flood damage to 251 homes and 13 businesses 
said gary talley spokesman for the state office of emergency 
services 
as the water moved downstream from here arkansas has 
experienced some of the worst flooding in decades as the arkansas 
and red rivers flowed over their banks hundreds of homes have been 
damaged 
the arkansas crested at pine bluff in central arkansas on 
wednesday and the red crested near texarkana texas at the 
texasarkansas line thursday morning but officials say rivers are 
receding so slowly and the ground is so saturated that the 
floodwaters will remain for days or even weeks 
after the rains lake texoma built in 1944 reached a record 
64476 feet almost 27 feet above the normal level and water 
roared over its spillway and down the red river for the first time 
since 1957 lake eufaula completed in 1964 also reached a record 
height 
the resulting flooding downstream led some arkansas farmers to 
unleash their frustrations at the meeting with clinton 
so many of them down there felt rightly or wrongly that the 
corps could have made different decisions over the last few months 
and there would be less flooding clinton said afterward 
one farmer asked if a task force could be established to 
evaluate the corps policies clinton said he thought that was a 
good suggestion 
but residents upstream from the lakes also have their questions 
wondering if the corps should have started to release water earlier 
jeff van cleave who runs the salty pelican restaurant on the 
shore of lake eufaula said he had to close april 27 because water 
had covered roads leading to the restaurant he wasnt able to 
reopen until wednesday 
it was a serious matter van cleave said thursday there 
were a lot of people concerned around here that they were holding 
the water back too long 
but van cleave acknowledged that eufaula is a flood control lake 
and said corps officials must concern themselves with downstream 
flooding as well as upstream problems 
i wouldnt take that job for all the tea in china he said 
at eufaula on thursday mist rose over the lake where 98000 
cubic feet of water was being released per second the amount of 
water being sent downstream was less than half the 230000 cubic 
feet per second released at the peak of the flooding last week but 
still more than twice the old record release rate of 40000 cubic 
feet per second said jim holderfield a corps supervisor at lake 
eufaula 
barbara craven a spokeswoman in the corps tulsa office said 
water was coming into the lake at up to 490000 cubic feet per 
second because of heavy rains and runoff from three rivers upstream 
without the reservoir she said people and businesses 
downstream would have had 490000 cubic feet per second come 
right at them 
by controlling the amount of water releases we bought a 
little time to prepare people downstream she said 
officials said they are more concerned with what lies ahead in 
the next six weeks typically the rainy season in oklahoma 
may is our wettest month ms craven said were looking 
at reservoirs that are filled to the brim right now were trying 
our best 
