<TEXT>
two dutch f16 jet fighters 
collided three miles over labrador on thursday during nato training 
maneuvers one pilot was injured while ejecting from his 
singleseat craft but there was no sign the second pilot survived 
the midafternoon collision occurred at 17000 feet about 45 
miles north of canadian forces base goose bay and 8 miles west of 
grand lake the canadian military said 
one pilot was seen to eject and has been reached by a canadian 
forces searchandrescue helicopter the forces said in a 
statement lt rein sneek based in lewarden the netherlands was 
airlifted to a hospital in goose bay suffering from multiple 
abrasions and bruises a base spokesman said 
the spokesman lt jeff agnew said they had no idea how the 
crash occurred he said the military was hoping to get more 
information from the injured pilot who was hospitalized overnight 
for observation 
the search continues for the second pilot identified as capt 
leo vogt agnew said a nato aircraft in the area at the time of the 
crash saw no parachute from the second plane and that there was no 
evidence vogt was able to eject 
asked if lowlevel flying a practice long protested by natives 
in the area played a part in the accident agnew replied 
absolutely not 
a forces statement said the collision occurred at 17000 feet 
and was not due to lowlevel flying 
jets on lowlevel flights often dip as low as 100 feet from the 
ground the height of a tall tree 
the dutch aircraft were taking part in a nato air defense 
exercise 
known as the falcon the americanbuilt f16 is a singleengine 
fighter used by the us and dutch air forces 
the netherlands is among several nato countries that send 
hundreds of pilots each year to cfb goose bay to train in lowlevel 
flying and combat techniques 
innu who live in the area say the training flights which take 
