actor charlie farrell silent film 
star of seventh heaven and the tv father in the popular 1950s 
series my little margie died at his desert home it was 
disclosed thursday he was 89 
farrell died of heart failure sunday at his palm springs home 
said willim broman a deputy at the riverside county coroners 
office the coroner was involved because there was no attending 
physician at the time of death 
the actor was buried wednesday at welwood murray cemetery in 
palm springs 
farrell ran an exclusive palm springs tennis club for years and 
helped to boost the reputation of the desert resort as a hollywood 
mecca he even dabbled in politics serving as the citys mayor at 
one point 
born aug 9 1902 in walpole mass farrell came to california 
in 1923 seeking a show business career he stepped into 3aday 
extra roles then leapt into stardom with a minor role in the ten 
commandments the 1923 cecil b de mille production 
farrell retired from movies after making about 10 silents and 
more than 40 talkies 
it was in the 1927 silent seventh heaven that farrell and 
janet gaynor established themselves as the screens top heartbeats 
janet and i were in the top 10 boxoffice draws for two years 
after that even into talkies he said in a 1977 interview 
we had a string of real good pictures street angel sunnyside 
up seventh heaven was the best though 
seventh heaven walked away with the best director and 
actress oscars at the first academy awards 
with the invention of television farrell was brought into 
americas living rooms as a widower father opposite gale storm on 
150 episodes of my little margie 
i had a helluva career he said in a 1977 interview the 
truth of it was i didnt get along with the studio brass they 
wanted that cagney thing all the time so i got out 
before world war ii farrell was a polo fanatic who would play 
with will rogers at the humorists sunset boulevard ranch but he 
eventually moved to the desert and concentrated on tennis 
farrell and his actresswife virginia valli who died in 
september 1968 worked with partner ralph bellamy to develop the 
posh palm springs racquet club which became a popular refuge for 
hollywood elite 
he was very affable a wonderful friend bellamy said 
thursday after learning of farrells death he was a great 
greeter and a great backslapper much better than i was he was 
the perfect fella to run the club 
when they started the club in 1934 there were less than 200 
people living there and no paved roads said bellamy 
the farrells were first citizens of the nowthriving desert 
community 100 miles east of los angeles they were probably as much 
responsible as anyone for the growth of palm springs from an indian 
reservation into a famed playground for millionaires 
there is no doubt about it the club started the popularity of 
palm springs and everybody liked charlie said bellamy 
farrell enjoyed running the club more than show business 
the club is more fun im playing tennis all the time and 
socializing but its harder work he said before selling the 
racquet club in 1959 
farrell was mayor of palm springs for six years from 1948 to 
1953 and he successfully fought efforts of gamblers intent on 
moving into the area 
his movie roles included parts in wings of youth sandy 
old ironsides the rough riders street angel 
fazil the red dance the river city girl lucky 
star sunny side up happy days high society blues 
girl without a room the big shakedown aggie appleby 
and the world is ours 
