<TEXT>
seven chinese peasants reportedly kidnapped 
shortly after they arrived in the united states for an exchange 
program apparently slipped away for some sightseeing in new york 
officials said thursday 
the massachusetts farmer who is hosting the rest of the group 
received a letter from the missing chinese police said it was the 
first contact since the farmers disappeared shortly after arriving 
at kennedy international airport on april 26 
the letter says they arranged to slip away from the airport and 
have been afraid to come forward since for fear of being deported 
as illegal immigrants said sgt thomas oreilly of the port 
authority of new york and new jersey 
the seven part of a group of 16 had been hustled into a 
waiting car at the airport according to their host molly aitken 
president of the world energy foundation she said she believed 
they had been abducted 
the port authority which operates the airport has been 
investigating the case as a possible kidnapping but officers 
suggested all along the disappearance could be a scheme to enter 
the country illegally 
federal involvement has been minimal 
the group from the fujian province in southern china was 
headed to ms aitkens farm in athol mass to study organic 
farming for 11 months 
the seven apparently wanted to see some of new york before 
heading off to rural massachusetts according to the letter 
oreilly said the letter was signed by three of the missing 
peasants and began by saying it was from all seven oreilly said 
the letter with no return address and a new york postmark 
arrived at aitkens green gables farm on wednesday and aitken 
telephoned port authority police 
investigators were always skeptical about the kidnapping theory 
questioning how three alleged abductors were able to grab seven 
people without using any weapons then stuff them into a small car 
apparently the missing chinese made contact with their friend at 
the airport and ran for the car oreilly said the letter said 
they planned to stay in town for a couple days and see chinatown 
but they have been unwilling to come forward for fear they may be 
deported or never see their families in china again 
oreilly said the port authority police havent any legal 
complaint against the seven and suggested they could smooth over 
any problems with the us immigration and naturalization service 
then their only problem would be with mainland china 
oreilly said 
