<TEXT>
government workers declared an 
indefinite strike and said they would take over state offices after 
president violeta barrios de chamorro suspended a civil service law 
on thursday 
the 60000member general federation of state workers said the 
strike included immediate takeover of installations and blocking 
of access by ministers and vice ministers of the government of mrs 
chamorro 
a federation communique said the government is preparing 
general conditions for massive firing of state workers 
earlier thursday mrs chamorro ordered another devaluation of 
nicaraguas currency the fourth in three weeks and steeply 
increased prices for utilities and public services 
adding to her woes in miami the contra rebels accused lefist 
sandinista holdovers in her administration of failing to live up to 
signed agreements and announced plans to stop demobilizing 
the president ordered the value of the cordoba cut by 9 percent 
in relation to the us dollar in her second devaluation in two 
days 
she also abolished government subsidies for transportation and 
raised rates for many staterun public services 
the price of running water was doubled electricity rates went 
up 300 percent and telephone service 1300 percent 
in announcing the painful measures presidential aide 
antonio lacayo said 10 years of sandinista rule left nicaragua 
badly and seriously bankrupt 
officials say there was only 3 million in the treasury and a 
foreign debt of 11 billion when mrs chamorro took office last 
month in this country of 35 million people 
the sandinistas devalued the cordoba 41 times last year and 
eight more times before leaving office on april 25 
when the sandinistas overthrew rightist dictator anastasio 
somoza and seized power in july 1979 the cordoba was traded at 10 
to the dollar on thursday 196472 cordobas bought 1 on the 
parallel market where most of the countrys money is traded 
lacayo said the chamorro administration had no idea nicaraguas 
economy was in such a shambles consequently measures will be 
deeper sharper weightier and more painful for the people and the 
country as a whole 
inflation hit 33600 percent in 1988 but dropped to 1800 
percent in 1989 there are no reliable estimates yet for this year 
mrs chamorro ordered a 60 percent pay increase for government 
employees wednesday workers protested it was not nearly enough to 
catch up with soaring prices and labor leaders rejected it 
laborers average about 44 a month and white collar workers 
about 100 
thousands of government employees at the national legislature 
the treasury labor and foreign ministries and elsewhere staged 
wildcat strikes 
hundreds of employees blocked the ministry entrance thursday and 
refused to let construction and transportation minister jaime 
icablzeta go in because he had fired an adviser a civil servant 
jose angel bermudez of the new national federation of workers 
which claims a membership of 61000 demanded a 200 percent 
increase for all wage earners 
the council for labor action and unity immediately backed him 
it is an arm of the communist party which forms part of mrs 
chamorros 14party united national opposition coalition 
about 80 contras turned in their weapons tuesday to united 
nations troops but spokesman alejandro acevedo said in miami no 
more rebels would do that 
he said the procedure was being reevaluated this could slow 
the process of disarmament 
the rebels once backed by the united states complain that the 
demobilization agreement signed may 4 by their commanders and mrs 
chamorro was being subverted by former sandinista officials who 
still dominate many ministries especially the military 
acevedo put the number of contra fighters still holding arms at 
more than 12000 but most independent observers say their forces 
have been reduced to a few thousand 
