<TEXT>
novelist mario vargas llosa won the first 
round of presidential elections by a slightly smaller percentage of 
the vote than previously projected according to the official vote 
count thursday 
the national election board said the centerright vargas llosa 
won 276 percent of the vote in the april 8 election while centrist 
alberto fujimori captured 246 percent the rest of the vote went 
to other candidates 
postelection projections had shown vargas llosa winning 32 
percent of the vote to fujimoris 30 percent 
the second round of elections next month pits the two 
frontrunners against each other polls indicate fujimori leads 
vargas llosa author of such novels as aunt julia and the 
scriptwriter and the green house by 3 to 8 percentage points 
the official vote tally took more than one month to release 
because the results of 52157 polling stations in this rugged south 
american country had to be transported to the capital lima to be 
individually verified 
the government had to await for the final election results to 
announce the date of the final elections officials had said it 
would probably be june 3 but many now say it may be held on june 10 
the election took place in the midst of perus worst economic 
crisis this century the government is virtually bankrupt and the 
annual inflation rate is above 2000 percent 
the balloting showed luis alva castro candidate of the ruling 
populist aprista party of president alan garcia received only 191 
percent of the vote 
traditionally strong marxist parties also faired poorly 
henry pease of the united left coalition took only 7 percent of 
the vote while his former colleague alfonso barrantes of the 
socialist left alliance finished with only 41 percent 
another 153 percent of the ballots were blank or declared 
invalid and the remainder of votes went to smaller parties 
the official results show 199 percent of the 9823062 
registered voters did not take part in the election despite the 
threat of penalties including a 50 fine that almost equals a 
months wage for the average worker 
most of the absenteeism was in zones in the countrys central 
andean mountains where the maoistinspired shining path guerrillas 
launched a violent campaign to keep voters from the polls 
it was not clear whether the high absenteeism was due to voter 
fear or sympathy with the rebels analysts said 
more than 18000 people have died in political violence since 
the shining path launched its armed insurgency on may 17 1980 the 
day before national elections ending 12 years of military 
dictatorship 
